            <p class="eyebrow">Common causes</p>
            <h2>Why basement floor drains clog</h2>
            <p>These issues cause water backups, structural damage, mold, and mildew growth. Regular maintenance prevents costly problems.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="symptom-cards">
            <div class="symptom-card"><strong>Debris and sediment buildup</strong><span>Laundry lint, hair, soap residue, and dirt accumulate over time, narrowing the drain and restricting water flow.</span></div>
            <div class="symptom-card"><strong>Tree root invasions</strong><span>Roots seek moisture and can infiltrate cracked or aging basement drain lines, causing severe blockages.</span></div>
            <div class="symptom-card"><strong>Heavy rainfall and storm surges</strong><span>Overwhelmed systems back up when the sewer line cannot handle the volume, especially with existing partial blockages.</span></div>
            <div class="symptom-card"><strong>Aging or deteriorating pipes</strong><span>Older cast iron or clay pipes corrode and develop cracks that catch debris and restrict flow.</span></div>
            <div class="symptom-card"><strong>Improper grading or pipe slope</strong><span>Poorly graded basement lines allow sediment to settle and create low spots that trap waste.</span></div>
            <div class="symptom-card"><strong>Cracked or collapsed pipe sections</strong><span>Soil shifting or foundation settlement can damage basement drain lines, leading to pooling or flooding.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
